I assume it is no easier but given the levity with which Kashmiri men regard women who opt to leave their marriage, speakers like Rubina did not have a lot to look forward to, save for the job currently supporting her financially.

Will the Divorcee

Divorce, as I have mentioned in the past, is often considered a stigma on the woman, and this peppered our conversation.

“It’s not just me who needs to get over the stigma around divorce.” she told me. “My parents married me off to this man because there wasn’t anyone to look after them. I was as helpless to my situation as much as they are. And now when I need their support to become financially independent so I can get a job to support my parents, I can’t even count on them.”

Tabassum. Asif (Designer/RHF Architect)

But the context of ‘stigma’ around divorce is at play here. My Kashmiri Facebook friend who had divorced, and her fans in Kerala wish she could play Widow for the greater good of Kashmiri Manhood, a form of discourse that is not entirely unique to those who live and communicate in the echo chambers of social media (Mom always told me to look beyond my nose, when she referred to my nose, or when The Quran refers to noses.)
